In [45]:
#T-test to check the dependency of smoking on charges.
Ho = "Charges are same" # Null Hypothesis
Ha = "Charges are not same" # Alternate Hypothesis

a = np.array(ins_data[ins_data.smoker == "yes"].charges) # Smokers charges
b = np.array(ins_data[ins_data.smoker == "no"].charges) # Non-smokers charges

t, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(a,b, axis = 0) # Independent t-test

if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f"{Ha} as the p_value {p_value} < 0.05")
else:
    print(f"{Ho} as the p_value {p_value} > 0.05")

Charges are not same as the p_value 8.271435842177219e-283 < 0.05

Smokers carry high charges than non-smokers

In [48]:
# T-test to check dependency of bmi on sex
Ho = "sex has no effect on bmi"   # Null Hypothesis
Ha = "sex has an effect on bmi"   # Alternate Hypothesis

a = np.array(ins_data[ins_data.sex == 'male'].bmi)  # bmi values corresponding to males
b = np.array(ins_data[ins_data.sex == 'female'].bmi) # bmi values corresponding to females

t, p_value  = stats.ttest_ind(a,b, axis = 0)  # t-test

if p_value < 0.05:  
    print(f'{Ha} as the p_value {p_value.round()} < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'{Ho} as the p_value {p_value.round(1)} > 0.05')

sex has no effect on bmi as the p_value 0.1 > 0.05

Similar BMI for both male & female

# Chi_square test to check the smoking trend among sex
Ho = "Gender has no effect on smoking"   # Null Hypothesis
Ha = "Gender has an effect on smoking"   # Alternate Hypothesis

crosstab_1 = pd.crosstab(ins_data['sex'],ins_data['smoker'])  # Cross table of sex and smoker attributes

chi, p_value, dof, expected =  stats.chi2_contingency(crosstab_1)

if p_value < 0.05: 
    print(f'{Ha} as the p_value {p_value.round(3)} < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'{Ho} as the p_value {p_value.round(3)} > 0.05')

Ho = "No. of children has no effect on bmi"   # Null Hypothesis
Ha = "No. of children has an effect on bmi"   # Alternate Hypothesis

zero = data_female[data_female.children == 0]['bmi']
one = data_female[data_female.children == 1]['bmi']
two = data_female[data_female.children == 2]['bmi']


f_stat, p_value = stats.f_oneway(zero,one,two)


if p_value < 0.05:  
    print(f'{Ha} as the p_value {p_value.round(3)} < 0.05')
else:
    print(f'{Ho} as the p_value {p_value.round(3)} > 0.05')

No. of children has no effect on bmi as the p_value 0.716 > 0.05

BMI is not changed by the number of children.
